fields.description:
I ran in to a “fun” setup error state when building Confluence today. I was attempting to evaluate a Server instance, but accidentally started setting up a Data Center instance at one step. I attempted to remedy the situation, but the instance got sick and I couldn't recover it.

Here’s what I did:

# got to the license page;
# choose to generate a new trial licence,
# go to my.atlassian.com,
# generate a valid DC license,
# pop that in, hit next;
# get to the cluster setup page;
# realise “oh whoops, I don’t want clusters, I just want a server instance”;
# go back to my.atlassian.com,
# generate a valid server license,
# hit back in the web browser,
# paste in the valid server license, hit next;

I expected at this point for Confluence setup to start provisioning itself. However, i got a tonne of “unclassified errors” due to there being 0 tenants. 

[^conf-accidental-dc-then-server-setup-catalina.log]  [^conf-accidental-dc-then-server-setup.log] 

I wasn't able to recover the setup, so I threw away the confluence home directory and began the setup process fresh.

h3. Summary
Confluence installation process keeps falling at the setup database process when behind the proxy with SSL enabled. The installation process successful after disabling the SSL or bypassing the proxy, however, this is not acceptable in the environment that proxy and SSL is mandatory.

h3. Test Environment
* Confluence 6.11.2
* Nginx latest version with the self-signed certificate

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Download the latest version of the Confluence
# Configure Proxy with SSL, Nginx for example:
{code}
...
listen 443 default ssl;
ssl_certificate      /nginx.crt;
ssl_certificate_key  /nginx.key;
...
location / {
    client_max_body_size 100m;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Server $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    proxy_pass http://localhost:8090;
}
{code}
# Start Confluence installation
{code}
./start-confluence.sh
{code}
# Navigate to https://<your_proxy_url>
# Choose the production installation type
# Enter your license
# Connect to your database

h3. Expected Results
Installation should work

h3. Actual Results
H2 or external database thrown errors like the following and installation failed.
{code}
HTTP Status 500 - Unable to register MBean [com.atlassian.confluence.jmx.TaskQueueWrapper@b873267] with key 'Confluence:name=MailTaskQueue'; nested exception is javax.management.InstanceAlreadyExistsException: Confluence:name=MailTaskQueue

Error creating bean with name 'tenantedTransactionManager' defined in class path resource [databaseSubsystemContext.xml]: Invocation of init method failed; nested exception is org.springframework.beans.factory.BeanCreationException: Error creating bean with name 'tenantedLocalSessionFactoryBean5' defined in class path resource [productionDatabaseContext.xml]: Invocation of init method failed; nested exception is java.lang.IllegalStateException: premature SessionFactory initialisation, Hibernate properties have not yet been persisted in confluence.cfg.xml

Caused by: org.springframework.beans.factory.BeanCreationException: Error creating bean with name 'tenantedTransactionManager' defined in class path resource [databaseSubsystemContext.xml]: Invocation of init method failed; nested exception is org.springframework.beans.factory.BeanCreationException: Error creating bean with name 'tenantedLocalSessionFactoryBean5' defined in class path resource [productionDatabaseContext.xml]: Invocation of init method failed; nested exception is java.lang.IllegalStateException: premature SessionFactory initialisation, Hibernate properties have not yet been persisted in confluence.cfg.xml
{code}

h3. Notes
* Installation worked flawlessly with Jira and Bamboo

h3. Workaround for Nginx

Proxy timeout needs to be increased by adding the following parameters under the _server_ config of Confluence. The following values increases the timeout to 10minutes. 
{code}
  proxy_connect_timeout       600;
  proxy_send_timeout          600;
  proxy_read_timeout          600;
  send_timeout                600;
{code}

h3. Summary

Currently, we can sort or order the response of recentlyViewedSpaces() by fields available in the response. However, it would be great if we could order the response by timestamp of user viewed either asc or desc :

Sample REST API
{code}
GET /wiki/rest/api/search?cql=space in recentlyViewedSpaces(10) and type = space order by title desc
{code}
